Interpretation of classification on Cheese dataset

Roza Gruter

9/23/2020

Interpretation of results obtained with HAC

Interpretation by PCA

part <- as.factor(part)
levels(part) <- paste("cluster",1:K,sep=" ")
res.pca <- PCA(data.frame(part, dta), quali.sup=1, graph=FALSE) # normalized PCA


Eigenvalues and explained data variability
round(res.pca$eig, 3) %>%
  kbl(caption = "Eigenvalues and percentage of explained inertia", align="l") %>%
  kable_styling(font_size = 10) %>%
  kable_minimal()
Eigenvalues and percentage of explained inertia
eigenvalue percentage of variance cumulative percentage of variance
comp 1 5.049 56.101 56.101
comp 2 1.844 20.494 76.595
comp 3 0.868 9.642 86.237
comp 4 0.577 6.415 92.652
comp 5 0.355 3.947 96.599
comp 6 0.175 1.948 98.547
comp 7 0.097 1.083 99.630
comp 8 0.028 0.316 99.946
comp 9 0.005 0.054 100.000

First two components explain together 76% of information contained in the data. Third component seem fairly important as well, as it adds 10% of explained data variability.

Correlation circle - representation of variables
plot(res.pca,choix="var",title="Correlation circle of variables")


Looking at the correlation circle, all the vartiables are well representes on at least one of the first two dimensions. Quality of representation is slightly worst for retinol and folates, but it remains reasonable. Most variables are strongly positively correlatred with each other (lipides, calories, cholesterol, proteines, magnesium, calcium). Calcium and folates/retinol are negatively correlated.


Quick look at the observations
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(res.pca,invisible="quali",title="Cheese", graph.type = "classic", label="none")
plot(res.pca,invisible="quali",title="Cheese", graph.type = "classic")

There seem to be 4 groups of individuals: bottom-left (4 observations), top-left (1 observation), middle-right (4 observations) and middle cluster. Looking at cheese types bottom-left seem to be light cheeses, middle-right hard cheeses, everything else in the middle, and one cheese detaches from the rest (Fr.chevrepatemolle).

Overlying clusters obtained with HAC on the PCA
plot(res.pca,habillage=1,invisible="quali",title="", graph.type = "classic")

plot(res.pca,choix="var",title="Correlation circle of variables")


The results of clustering confirm fresh cheese class and hard cheese class, then the middle part is divided in three. Fr.chevrepatemolle was placed in the cluster 4, with three other cheeses.

Fresh cheeses and yoghurt are poor in nutritional content, situated at the oposite side of the variables. They are especially poor in cholesterol or calories from the bad, and calcium from the good. On the other hand we have hard chesses (parmesan, comt etc.) that are on the contrary rich in cholesterol and calories, but also rich in calcium or magnesium. Fr.chevrepatemolle is caracterized by high content of folates and retinol. A good cheese for pregnant women, or people who want to get rid of some wrinkles ;)

Interpretation of classification results using quantitative variables

des <- catdes(data.frame(part,dta), num.var=1)
About the partition
des$quanti.var %>%
  kbl(caption = "Correlation coefficient between the partition and variables", align="l") %>%
  kable_styling(font_size = 10) %>%
  kable_minimal()
Correlation coefficient between the partition and variables
Eta2 P-value

lipides 0.8686058 0.0000000
proteines 0.8466645 0.0000000
cholesterol 0.8246679 0.0000000
folates 0.8127466 0.0000000
magnesium 0.7454905 0.0000007
sodium 0.7175624 0.0000025
retinol 0.6517571 0.0000281
calcium 0.5364837 0.0007315

This partition is best characterized by calories, lipides, proteines, cholesterol and folates, but overall all the variables play an important role in the definition of the partition.

Classes (HAC)
